#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.nonzero:43
msgid ""
"While the nonzero values can be obtained with ``a[nonzero(a)]``, it is "
"recommended to use ``x[x.astype(np.bool)]`` or ``x[x != 0]`` instead, which "
"will correctly handle 0-d arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.nonzero:49
msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.nonzero:71
msgid ""
"A common use for ``nonzero`` is to find the indices of an array, where a "
"condition is True.  Given an array `a`, the condition `a` > 3 is a boolean "
"array and since False is interpreted as 0, np.nonzero(a > 3) yields the "
"indices of the `a` where the condition is true."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.nonzero:84
msgid ""
"Using this result to index `a` is equivalent to using the mask directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.nonzero:91
msgid "``nonzero`` can also be called as a method of the array."
msgstr ""

